nd":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England.":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1375–1460":"1375–1460","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1406–1490":"1406–1490","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1490":"1490","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1378":"1378","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","about 1400":"about 1400","1406 ":"1406","1406":"1406","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England.":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Pope II was born in 1375, in Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, his father, John Pope I, was 35 and his mother, wife John Pope I, was 30. He married Mary Spencer in 1398, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1460, in his hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1375–1460":"1375–1460","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1406–1490":"1406–1490","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1490":"1490","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1378":"1378","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1406 ":"1406","1406":"1406","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England.":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1375–1460":"1375–1460","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1406–1490":"1406–1490","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1450":"1450","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1490":"1490","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1378":"1378","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","about 1400":"noin 1400","1406 ":"1406","1406":"1406","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England.":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1375–1460":"1375–1460","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1406–1490":"1406–1490","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Décédée","1450":"1450","1340